Mexico is the Global music industry market share data|second-largest Spanish-speaking music market in the world, slightly behind Spain, based on retail value.<ref>cite web |url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/riaj/pdf/issue/industry/RIAJ2006E.pdf|title=RIAJ: Yearbook 2006, IFPI 2004 Report (Page 23)|publisher=Recording Industry Association of Japan|accessdate=11 November 2017</ref><ref>cite web |url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/riaj/open/open-record!file?fid=1474|title=RIAJ Yearbook 2017: IFPI Global Music Report 2017  (Page 5)|publisher=Recording Industry Association of Japan|accessdate=11 November 2017</ref> Although long plagued by piracy,<ref>cite web | url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2006/07/05/illegal-downloads-piracy-accepted-in-mexican-music-market.html | title=Illegal Downloads, Piracy Accepted in Mexican Music Market | author=Associated Press | publisher=Fox News | accessdate=11 November 2017</ref> the domestic market has strengthened in recent years due to strong growth from digital and streaming services, which account for 66% of the overall value, according to the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry.<ref>cite web | url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2017.pdf | title=Global Music Report 2017 | publisher=International Federation of the Phonographic Industry | accessdate=11 November 2017</ref> The following list covers the top-selling albums released in the country based on figures compiled by the Mexican Association of Producers of Phonograms and Videograms, better known as AMPROFON by its initials in Spanish, from 1999 onwards.<ref>cite web | url=http://www.amprofon.com.mx/certificaciones-amprofon.php?disquera=&anio=&tipoAlbum=&tipoCertificacion=&aniocer=&key=&action=Buscar | title=Certificaciones | publisher=AMPROFON | accessdate=11 November 2017</ref>

Information published by magazines, tabloids or local newspapers is excluded, as it is not supported by reliable sources such as AMPROFON. For instance, Mexico City-based newspaper El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal claims that 1984 release ''Las Mañanitas'' by Pedro Infante is the best-selling album of all-time in the country, with more than 20 million copies sold, but lacks reliable sources.<ref>cite news | url=http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/418209.html | title=Tiene Pedro Infante el disco más vendido de la historia de México | newspaper=El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal | date=April 12, 2007 | accessdate=1 January 2017</ref>

